<br>
I read the threads about class roles and what everyone had to say about them and what would be the best group composition.  I must say I learned many things from it.  It was all very interesting, even the disagreements (well, especially the disagreements ;-).  But it all seemed very... hmmm... Theoretical to me :-)<br>
<br>
I hunted with a group with a &quot;correct&quot; composition only once so far, and it was in a well-organized guild raid in Runnyeye.  We had a wizard, a cleric, an enchanter, a monk and two rogues.  That's the closest I ever came to the group composition suggested by some notable scholars and theoricians visiting this board :-)  I'm level 30 now and a rogue.  I pulled and tanked for a group made up of me and three clerics a couple times.  Yesterday, I shared the meat shield job (tanking) with a shaman for a full group made up mostly of int casters.  Who said rangers should not try to tank? ;-)  Advices on class role and best group composition are hmmm... interesting :-)<br>
<br>
Now, I know this post has to sound like a rant, so I would like to add a few things about what I consider to be &quot;The perfect group&quot;.  <br>
<br>
1)  No freaky loot hogs.<br>
People who loot corpses before the fights are over are the worse.<br>
<br>
2) People who learned languages beside their own.<br>
I am getting tired to have to translate for the elves and humans who did not bother to learn each other languages.  I think by level 30, any good elf who does not speak human and any human who does not speak elvish should stop whatever ther are doing and learn a second language :-)  I don't know if this is as common a problem with the dark races.  I know most gnomes and dwarves I met knew a couple secondary languages.  Maybe the elves and humans just have it too easy from the start and never see the point of learning languages until much later in game though... <br>
<br>
3) A leader.<br>
I'm not even asking for a good leader, just to have one!<br>
What I mean by leader is someone who is in charge of deciding with the puller when it's time to invite critters to the party.  I also mean someone who will confront the loot hogs about their greedy behavior.  Once, we had this druid in the group who was leader.  He was in charge of calling the names of people whose turn to loot it was.  Alpha loot with a hall monitor ;-)  But it worked well and the casters had a fair share for once.  <br>
<br>
When I think of what would constitute the perfect group, that's the first things that come to mind.  Group composition is not something I expect to be worried about before I'm level 45 or more.  Until then, I will enjoy the new challenges and opportunities unusual group mixes offer.  I say let us be creative and original while we can.  I say let's try new things every day :-)<br>
<br>
But thanks for the advices everyone :-)<br>
<br>
Soyin,<br>
Gnomish kabob of the 30th seasoning<br>
Circle of Sisters<br>
