<br>
&quot;The Perfect Group&quot;:<br>
The core of a perfect or well balanced group finds root in what is sometimes called the &quot;golden triangle&quot; or the &quot;holy trinity&quot;:  a Warrior (meat-shield, aggro-manager, damage dealer), a Cleric (hp and ac buffer, damage healer, and ressurecter) and an Enchanter (crowd controller and buffer (melee haste and caster clarity).  <br>
<br>
The &quot;trinity&quot; slots can, to a certain extent, be subsituted for other classes:<br>
Warrior - paladin, monk, sk, ranger, rogue, bard - not necessarily in that order;<br>
Cleric - druid, shaman, paladin, necromancer (yes smart necros can keep a tank alive);<br>
Enchanter - any class that has root or mez/stun can sort of stand-in for an enchanter...but in truth there is no real replacement for an enchanter.<br>
<br>
The problem with substitution is that the further you stray from the core classes (particularly with the cleric and enchanter) the more inefficient the group becomes (i.e. more downtime for inefficient healers to med up and the more time spent trying to &quot;pull singles&quot; without the benefit of safe crowd control).<br>
<br>
With a solid trinity built, the remaining 3 slots are all about tweaking or &quot;greasing the wheels&quot; as I like to call it.  As an example, a necro is an excellent &quot;wheel greaser&quot; in a group:  he can give mana to the cleric and enchanter (or any other caster for that matter), his low cost dots add efficient damage to each mob, his pet likewise adds more melee damage without sacrificing a group slot, he can perform very efficient damage reduction (by the way of dot heals), he can help split and control very mess pulls by way of mez, root, invulnerability and feign death and he can also ressurect in a crunch to cut down on corpse recovery time.  <br>
<br>
This is true of almost every other caster class, althought they do it in different ways (shamans have excellent dots, their massive slows reduce the amount of mana spent by clerics healing, their buffs enhance the damage dealt by tanks, their regeneration decreases the amount of damage taken by tanks, etc....)<br>
<br>
Aside from the social perspective (grouping with nice people), the perfect group is whatever you feel comfortable with in a given situation.  For example, if I was in deep chardok or howling stones, I would want a necro with me who could res as in a wipeout situation (assuming the necro was able to FD safely) he/she would cut-down on corpse recovery dramatically.<br>
<br>
Anyhew, my 2 cp.<br>
<br>
Rexfelix<br>
